<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>


<section xml:id="lesson4_4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Summary</title>


    <p> To summarize, let's step through the example you just solved. We want to understand the
        behavior we see when we place a measurement betweeen two <c>H</c> gates.</p>
    <p>
        <image source="L4.3-measure-in-h-gate-2.png" width="90%" />
    </p>


    <p> That measurement collapses the superposition after the first <c>H</c> gate, so the second <c>H</c>
        gate is receiving a qubit that is either <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m>, not a qubit in superposition.
        The second <c>H</c> gate then places the qubit back into superposition, but the phase is
        unknown. The second measurement then collapses the superposition, and the outcome is either <m>\ket{0}</m>
        or <m>\ket{1}</m> with equal probability.</p>

    <p>
        <image source="L4.3-summary-2.png" width="90%" />
    </p>

    <p> If there is no measurement between the <c>H</c> gates, however, the second <c>H</c> gate
        receives an input that is in superposition with a 50/50 probability of being <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m>
        and phase corresponding to whether the initial input was black or white. The second <c>H</c>
        gate then places the qubit back into a state that is either <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m> with 100%
        probability, depending on the initial input.</p>


    <p>
        <image source="L4.3-summary-1.png" width="90%" />
    </p>


</section>
